column169: DURING THE PRE-LOAD OPERATIONS AT THE UPS UTRECHT FACILITY IN THE NETHERLANDS ONE PACKAGE FELT WARM TO THE TOUCH AND SHOWED SIGNS OF SMOKE. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING AND SECURED.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE FLAMES OBSERVED. DURING INNER CONTENT INSPECTION THERE IS EVIDENCE OF BURNING, MELTING, AND CHARRING OF THE INNER CONTENTS. THE INCIDENT PACKAGE WAS MARKED AND LABELLED AS UN3480, LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965 WITH A CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY AND CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY LABEL. THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A THREE PACKAGE SHIPMENT WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AND HAD PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT IN HONG KONG ON 15-NOV-2024. THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM HKG - SHJ - CGN BEFORE EXPERIENCING THE THERMAL EVENT IN UTRECHT, NETHERLANDS. THERE ARE TWO ADDITIONAL PACKAGES IN THE SHIPMENT THAT WERE ALSO REMOVED AND SECURED, TRACKING NUMBERS 1Z802E150499401436 AND 1Z802E150495846446. THESE TWO PACKAGES WERE NOT INVOLVED IN THE LITHIUM BATTERY EVENT. THE PACKAGE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON 04-DEC-2024, REPORT NUMBER 1417932.

column169: On December 7, 2024, at 1751 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Farragut, TN regarding the release of  BPW 76910 Antifoam. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 0.5 gallons of BPW 76910 Antifoam (UN3082, 9, III) from (1) 330-gallon poly tote onto the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot. The release was reportedly due to a crack in the tote, impacting a 4’ x 6’ area on the trailer and a 1’ x 3’ area of asphalt. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. Contractors transferred the remaining product into a new 330-gallon poly tote to continue on with the client’s shipment and took the damaged tote off-site for proper disposal. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DM, which was then taken off site by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 15-gallon drum containing hazardous product, Nalco Stabrex#ST70. The contractor used sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the release and applied oil dry to clean-up the spill. The damaged drum was overpacked into one 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. The neutralized and impacted oil dry was containerized into a separate 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste generated from the spill response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: Drums arrived to service center 151 and were unloaded. No damage or leaks were noted at the time. When the freight was being prepped to be loaded into another trailer, it was discovered that one of the drums was leaking from a seal. The leak is contained to the drum and the pallet the drum is on. Sa fety advised CURA would be contacted to send a crew out to clean the drum and inspect the seal and move the drum into a recovery drum if necessary.
column170: Instruct dock crews to inspect hazardous materials freight as it is moved on and off trailers to ensure spills are discovered and cleaned quickly.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XNW experienced a UN2920 Dicoco Dimethyl Ammonium Chloride release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4 ounces of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the poly tote lid due to a loose cap. The cap was tightened and re-secured onto the tote. The tote was then decontaminated, wiped down, and secured for continued shipment on. The impacted pads used to clean the tote were containerized into a 5-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

During the unloading phase of trailer, employee was attempting to unload a pallet of freight with a forklift, the forklift blades were protruding past the pallet and punctured a box in front of the pallet. Contact was made at the bottom side of the box putting a 1/2 inch long puncture in the box that caused a puncture to the inner packaging. Inner packaging was then taken out placed in a position to where the material would not leak further. All spillage of material was confined to immediate area for cleanup
